SIMPLE: splay
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Splay
<hw>Splay</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Abbrev. of
<ets>display</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To display; to spread.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Our ensigns <xex>splayed</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Gascoigne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To dislocate, as a shoulder bone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To spay; to castrate.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To turn on one side; to render oblique; to slope or
slant, as the side of a door, window, etc.</def> <rj><au>Oxf.
Gloss.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Splay</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Splay
<hw>Splay</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Displayed; spread out; turned
outward; hence, flat; ungainly; <as>as, <ex>splay</ex>
shoulders</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sonwthing <qex>splay</qex>, something blunt-edged, unhandy, and
infelicitous.</q> <rj><qau>M. Arnold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Splay</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Splay
<hw>Splay</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A slope or bevel,
especially of the sides of a door or window, by which the opening is
made larged at one face of the wall than at the other, or larger at each
of the faces than it is between them.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Splayfoot</ent>⟦br⟧
